<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="374" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,289,926]" pageId="2" pageNumber="374">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,289,314]" pageId="2" pageNumber="374">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Body pale with weakly patterned wings (known species with an entirely pale frons); head and thoracic carinae distinct, concolorous with body. Aedeagus bearing a ventral projection (unique among New World 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Leach" authorityYear="1815" box="[151,279,361,386]" class="Insecta" family="Delphacidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="374" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Delphacini">Delphacini</taxonomicName>
); pygofer opening without ventral processes, anal tube (=segment X) without processes.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,289,926]" pageId="2" pageNumber="374">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,466,397,422]" pageId="2" pageNumber="374">Amended description.</emphasis>
Elongate and slender forms. Head narrower than pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[1190,1288,397,422]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1954,1976]" captionTargetBox="[159,1427,968,1933]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[159,1428,968,1933]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Abbrosoga errata Caldwell, male holotype except D (Maricao State Forest); A. dorsal habitus, B. front, C. lateral habitus, D. hind leg and metatibial spur, ventral view, E. labels." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2601141/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="374">Figs 1A</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1304,1341,398,422]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1560,1582]" captionTargetBox="[172,1427,414,1538]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[159,1427,411,1538]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Abbrosoga multispinosa Otero and Bartlett, male paratype, Mayagüez, P.R. A. dorsal habitus, B. front, C. lateral habitus, D. dorsal view, head and thorax, E. male terminalia, lateral view, F. male terminalia, caudal view, G. lateral view, head and thorax." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2601147/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="374">3A</figureCitation>
), vertex weakly projected in front of eyes. Vertex and frons broad, fastigium rounded (
<figureCitation box="[1035,1127,433,458]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1954,1976]" captionTargetBox="[159,1427,968,1933]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[159,1428,968,1933]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Abbrosoga errata Caldwell, male holotype except D (Maricao State Forest); A. dorsal habitus, B. front, C. lateral habitus, D. hind leg and metatibial spur, ventral view, E. labels." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2601141/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="374">Figs 1C</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1141,1177,433,457]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1560,1582]" captionTargetBox="[172,1427,414,1538]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[159,1427,411,1538]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Abbrosoga multispinosa Otero and Bartlett, male paratype, Mayagüez, P.R. A. dorsal habitus, B. front, C. lateral habitus, D. dorsal view, head and thorax, E. male terminalia, lateral view, F. male terminalia, caudal view, G. lateral view, head and thorax." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2601147/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="374">3C</figureCitation>
). Medial facial carinae forking near fastigium (
<figureCitation box="[430,525,469,494]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1954,1976]" captionTargetBox="[159,1427,968,1933]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[159,1428,968,1933]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Abbrosoga errata Caldwell, male holotype except D (Maricao State Forest); A. dorsal habitus, B. front, C. lateral habitus, D. hind leg and metatibial spur, ventral view, E. labels." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2601141/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="374">Figs 1B</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[542,577,470,494]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1560,1582]" captionTargetBox="[172,1427,414,1538]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[159,1427,411,1538]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Abbrosoga multispinosa Otero and Bartlett, male paratype, Mayagüez, P.R. A. dorsal habitus, B. front, C. lateral habitus, D. dorsal view, head and thorax, E. male terminalia, lateral view, F. male terminalia, caudal view, G. lateral view, head and thorax." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2601147/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="374">3B</figureCitation>
). Median carina of vertex weak. Lateral carinae of pronotum not clearly reaching posterior margin. Hind leg (
<figureCitation box="[574,663,505,530]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1954,1976]" captionTargetBox="[159,1427,968,1933]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[159,1428,968,1933]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Abbrosoga errata Caldwell, male holotype except D (Maricao State Forest); A. dorsal habitus, B. front, C. lateral habitus, D. hind leg and metatibial spur, ventral view, E. labels." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2601141/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="374">Fig. 1D</figureCitation>
) with 2 lateral spines, 1 near femoral-tibial joint, 1 near midlength; tibial apex with 5 spinules, arranged 3+2. Basitarsus with 7 apical spinules, arranged 5+2, second tarsomere with row of 4 spinules. Forewing (
<figureCitation box="[482,573,577,602]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1954,1976]" captionTargetBox="[159,1427,968,1933]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[159,1428,968,1933]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Abbrosoga errata Caldwell, male holotype except D (Maricao State Forest); A. dorsal habitus, B. front, C. lateral habitus, D. hind leg and metatibial spur, ventral view, E. labels." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2601141/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="374">Figs 1C</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[586,619,577,601]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1560,1582]" captionTargetBox="[172,1427,414,1538]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[159,1427,411,1538]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Abbrosoga multispinosa Otero and Bartlett, male paratype, Mayagüez, P.R. A. dorsal habitus, B. front, C. lateral habitus, D. dorsal view, head and thorax, E. male terminalia, lateral view, F. male terminalia, caudal view, G. lateral view, head and thorax." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2601147/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="374">3C</figureCitation>
) elongate, mostly clear with diffuse patterning (in distal cubital area and less often in costal region), with an elongate dark spot on commissural margin at apex of claval veins. Forewing venation (
<figureCitation box="[264,333,649,674]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1718,1740]" captionTargetBox="[352,1219,1331,1596]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[340,1247,1286,1669]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 6. Abbrosoga multispinosa Otero and Bartlett, wing venation (from left wing of paratype)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2601153/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="374">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
) with Sc and RA unbranched, RP 3 branched, M unbranched and CuA 2–3 branched. Metatibial spur foliaceous and tectiform, row of many fine, black-tipped teeth on posterior margin. Male genitalia with pygofer subquadrate in lateral view (
<figureCitation box="[570,663,721,746]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,2004,2026]" captionTargetBox="[285,1300,1345,1983]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[285,1301,1345,1983]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Abbrosoga errata Caldwell, male terminalia (Maricao State Forest), A. caudal view, B. left lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2601145/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="374">Figs 2B</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[676,709,722,746]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1560,1582]" captionTargetBox="[172,1427,414,1538]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[159,1427,411,1538]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Abbrosoga multispinosa Otero and Bartlett, male paratype, Mayagüez, P.R. A. dorsal habitus, B. front, C. lateral habitus, D. dorsal view, head and thorax, E. male terminalia, lateral view, F. male terminalia, caudal view, G. lateral view, head and thorax." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2601147/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="374">3E</figureCitation>
), distinctly taller than wide; opening in caudal view subcircular with rounded margins (
<figureCitation box="[441,544,757,782]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,2004,2026]" captionTargetBox="[285,1300,1345,1983]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[285,1301,1345,1983]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Abbrosoga errata Caldwell, male terminalia (Maricao State Forest), A. caudal view, B. left lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2601145/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="374">Figs 2A</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[566,598,758,782]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1560,1582]" captionTargetBox="[172,1427,414,1538]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[159,1427,411,1538]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Abbrosoga multispinosa Otero and Bartlett, male paratype, Mayagüez, P.R. A. dorsal habitus, B. front, C. lateral habitus, D. dorsal view, head and thorax, E. male terminalia, lateral view, F. male terminalia, caudal view, G. lateral view, head and thorax." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2601147/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="374">3F</figureCitation>
), lacking projections. Gonostyli (=parameres) (
<figureCitation box="[1178,1279,757,782]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1005,1027]" captionTargetBox="[179,1392,223,964]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[160,1426,193,983]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Abbrosoga errata Caldwell, male terminalia line art (redrawn from Caldwell and Martorell 1951), A. male terminalia, left lateral view; B. aedeagus, right lateral view; C. gonostyli, caudal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2601149/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="374">Figs 4C</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1301,1336,757,782]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1161,1183]" captionTargetBox="[278,1284,514,1106]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[270,1317,506,1115]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 5. Abbrosoga multispinosa Otero and Bartlett, male genitalia, line art, A. left gonostylus, widest view; B. aedeagus, left lateral view (slightly rotated clockwise)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2601151/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="374">5A</figureCitation>
) simple (unbranched), basal angle small; proximally diverging, apex medially converging in distal forth. Aedeagus (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1005,1027]" captionTargetBox="[179,1392,223,964]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[160,1426,193,983]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Abbrosoga errata Caldwell, male terminalia line art (redrawn from Caldwell and Martorell 1951), A. male terminalia, left lateral view; B. aedeagus, right lateral view; C. gonostyli, caudal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2601149/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="374">Figs 4B</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[199,233,829,854]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1161,1183]" captionTargetBox="[278,1284,514,1106]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[270,1317,506,1115]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 5. Abbrosoga multispinosa Otero and Bartlett, male genitalia, line art, A. left gonostylus, widest view; B. aedeagus, left lateral view (slightly rotated clockwise)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2601151/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="374">5B</figureCitation>
) strongly curved ventrally, subtended with slender process(es). Aedeagal base closely approximating anal tube (aedeagal base symmetrical), suspensorium O-shaped, surrounding base of aedeagus including subtending process, stem of suspensorium (between aedeagus and anal tube) short. Male anal tube unarmed.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
