<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="375" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,1221]" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,151,176]" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">Remarks.</emphasis>
Superficially, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Caldwell" authorityYear="1951" box="[485,607,151,176]" class="Insecta" family="Delphacidae" genus="Abbrosoga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="375" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[485,607,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">Abbrosoga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to other pale 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Leach" authorityYear="1815" box="[892,1018,151,176]" class="Insecta" family="Delphacidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="375" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Delphacini">Delphacini</taxonomicName>
, such as 
<taxonomicName authority="Distant" authorityName="Distant" authorityYear="1906" box="[1128,1275,151,176]" class="Insecta" family="Delphacidae" genus="Toya" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="375" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1128,1181,153,176]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">Toya</emphasis>
Distant
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Wagner" authorityName="Wagner" authorityYear="1963" class="Insecta" family="Delphacidae" genus="Metadelphax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="375" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1290,1436,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">Metadelphax</emphasis>
Wagner
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Bartlett &amp; Webb" authorityName="Bartlett &amp; Webb" authorityYear="2014" box="[253,615,188,213]" class="Insecta" family="Delphacidae" genus="Spartidelphax" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="375" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[253,410,188,213]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">Spartidelphax</emphasis>
Bartlett &amp; Webb
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Fennah" authorityName="Fennah" authorityYear="1963" box="[628,853,188,213]" class="Insecta" family="Delphacidae" genus="Syndelphax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="375" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[628,757,188,213]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">Syndelphax</emphasis>
Fennah
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Fennah" authorityName="Fennah" authorityYear="1956" box="[867,1065,188,213]" class="Insecta" family="Delphacidae" genus="Sogatella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="375" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[867,973,188,213]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">Sogatella</emphasis>
Fennah
</taxonomicName>
or perhaps 
<taxonomicName authority="Asche &amp; Wilson. The" authorityName="Asche &amp; Wilson. The" authorityYear="1990" class="Insecta" family="Delphacidae" genus="Tagosodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="375" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1206,1323,188,213]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">Tagosodes</emphasis>
Asche &amp; Wilson. The
</taxonomicName>
dorsum of the mesonotum bears a narrow, weak median vitta, unlike the strong vitta of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fennah" authorityYear="1956" box="[1282,1388,223,248]" class="Insecta" family="Delphacidae" genus="Sogatella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="375" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1282,1388,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">Sogatella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Asche &amp; Wilson. The" authorityYear="1990" box="[151,268,260,285]" class="Insecta" family="Delphacidae" genus="Tagosodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="375" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,268,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">Tagosodes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Unlike 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wagner" authorityYear="1963" box="[369,515,260,285]" class="Insecta" family="Delphacidae" genus="Metadelphax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="375" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[369,515,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">Metadelphax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Distant" authorityYear="1906" box="[531,582,261,284]" class="Insecta" family="Delphacidae" genus="Toya" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="375" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[531,582,261,284]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">Toya</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bartlett &amp; Webb" authorityYear="2014" box="[601,758,260,285]" class="Insecta" family="Delphacidae" genus="Spartidelphax" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="375" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[601,758,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">Spartidelphax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and some 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fennah" authorityYear="1963" box="[884,1013,260,285]" class="Insecta" family="Delphacidae" genus="Syndelphax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="375" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[884,1013,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">Syndelphax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the frons is entirely pale, instead of bearing dark markings near the carinae. The wings are diffusely patterned unlike macropterous 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fennah" authorityYear="1963" box="[1247,1376,295,320]" class="Insecta" family="Delphacidae" genus="Syndelphax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="375" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1247,1376,295,320]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">Syndelphax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The form of the terminalia, and the aedeagus in particular, contrasts with all these genera; the aedeagus of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Caldwell" authorityYear="1951" box="[1314,1436,332,357]" class="Insecta" family="Delphacidae" genus="Abbrosoga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="375" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1314,1436,332,357]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">Abbrosoga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
bears a subtending process that is not found in any of these other genera.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,1221]" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">
It is possible that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Caldwell" authorityYear="1951" box="[404,526,404,429]" class="Insecta" family="Delphacidae" genus="Abbrosoga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="375" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[404,526,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">Abbrosoga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is phylogenetically most closely allied with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Caldwell" authorityYear="1951" box="[1039,1178,404,429]" class="Insecta" family="Delphacidae" genus="Phrictopyga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="375" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1039,1178,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">Phrictopyga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Caldwell" authorityYear="1951" box="[1236,1354,405,428]" class="Insecta" family="Delphacidae" genus="Pygospina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="375" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1236,1354,405,428]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">Pygospina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in that they are all pale taxa, with a weak median vitta (absent in 
<taxonomicName authority="Otero &amp; Bartlett, 2019" authorityName="Otero &amp; Bartlett" authorityYear="2019" box="[798,972,439,464]" class="Insecta" family="Delphacidae" genus="Abbrosoga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="375" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="multispinosa" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[798,972,439,464]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">A. multispinosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[979,1042,439,464]" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[979,1042,439,464]" pageId="3" pageNumber="375" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
), diffusely pale wings, and bearing (at least between 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Caldwell" authorityYear="1951" box="[354,472,477,500]" class="Insecta" family="Delphacidae" genus="Pygospina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="375" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[354,472,477,500]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">Pygospina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Caldwell" authorityYear="1951" box="[532,654,476,501]" class="Insecta" family="Delphacidae" genus="Abbrosoga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="375" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[532,654,476,501]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">Abbrosoga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) similarities in the male genitalia (shape of pygofer, parameres and aedeagus). However, both 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Caldwell" authorityYear="1951" box="[452,570,513,536]" class="Insecta" family="Delphacidae" genus="Pygospina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="375" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[452,570,513,536]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">Pygospina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Caldwell" authorityYear="1951" box="[626,764,511,536]" class="Insecta" family="Delphacidae" genus="Phrictopyga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="375" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[626,764,511,536]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">Phrictopyga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are slightly laterally compressed with the pygofer and anal tube bearing processes that are absent in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Caldwell" authorityYear="1951" box="[609,731,548,573]" class="Insecta" family="Delphacidae" genus="Abbrosoga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="375" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[609,731,548,573]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">Abbrosoga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,1221]" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">
<bibRefCitation author="Caldwell, J. S. &amp; Martorell, L. F." box="[199,521,583,608]" pageId="3" pageNumber="375" pagination="133 - 269" refId="ref6483" refString="Caldwell, J. S. &amp; Martorell, L. F. (1951 dated 1950) Review of the Auchenorynchous Homoptera of Puerto Rico. Part II. The Fulgoroidea except Kinnaridae. Journal of Agriculture of the University of Puerto Rico, 34 (2), 133 - 269." type="journal article" year="1951">Caldwell &amp; Martorell (1951)</bibRefCitation>
compared 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Caldwell" authorityYear="1951" box="[644,766,583,608]" class="Insecta" family="Delphacidae" genus="Abbrosoga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="375" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[644,766,583,608]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">Abbrosoga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to 
<taxonomicName authority="Distant and Columbisoga Muir." authorityName="Distant and Columbisoga Muir." box="[801,1295,583,608]" class="Insecta" family="Delphacidae" genus="Nilaparvata" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="375" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[801,936,583,608]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">Nilaparvata</emphasis>
Distant and 
<emphasis box="[1077,1227,583,608]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">Columbisoga</emphasis>
Muir.
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicName box="[1300,1435,583,608]" class="Insecta" family="Delphacidae" genus="Nilaparvata" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="375" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1300,1435,583,608]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">Nilaparvata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has teeth on the basitarsus of the hind legs, a synapomorphy of the genus. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Muir" authorityYear="1921" box="[1068,1217,620,645]" class="Insecta" family="Delphacidae" genus="Columbisoga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="375" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1068,1217,620,645]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">Columbisoga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may have similar coloration and also has a similar structure of the aedeagus (i.e., bearing a ventral projection), but is in the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Muir" authorityYear="1915" box="[151,346,692,717]" class="Insecta" family="Delphacidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="375" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Tropidocephalini">Tropidocephalini</taxonomicName>
, and lacks teeth on the calcar (and the distinct suspensorium found in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Leach" authorityYear="1815" box="[1130,1258,692,717]" class="Insecta" family="Delphacidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="375" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Delphacini">Delphacini</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,1221]" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">
All available specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Caldwell" authorityYear="1951" box="[515,619,728,752]" class="Insecta" family="Delphacidae" genus="Abbrosoga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="375" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="errata">
<emphasis box="[515,619,728,752]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">A. errata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were collected at relatively high elevations, above 
<quantity box="[1217,1300,727,752]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.096" pageId="3" pageNumber="375" unit="ft" value="2000.0">2000 ft</quantity>
(
<quantity box="[1318,1395,727,752]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.1" pageId="3" pageNumber="375" unit="m" value="610.0">610 m</quantity>
) as reported by 
<bibRefCitation author="Caldwell, J. S. &amp; Martorell, L. F." box="[288,637,764,789]" pageId="3" pageNumber="375" pagination="133 - 269" refId="ref6483" refString="Caldwell, J. S. &amp; Martorell, L. F. (1951 dated 1950) Review of the Auchenorynchous Homoptera of Puerto Rico. Part II. The Fulgoroidea except Kinnaridae. Journal of Agriculture of the University of Puerto Rico, 34 (2), 133 - 269." type="journal article" year="1951">Caldwell and Martorell (1951)</bibRefCitation>
. In contrast, specimens of 
<taxonomicName authority="Otero &amp; Bartlett, 2019" authorityName="Otero &amp; Bartlett" authorityYear="2019" box="[939,1115,764,789]" class="Insecta" family="Delphacidae" genus="Abbrosoga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="375" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="multispinosa" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[939,1115,764,789]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">A. multispinosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1122,1186,764,789]" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1122,1186,764,789]" pageId="3" pageNumber="375" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
were collected at low elevation (the 
<typeStatus box="[310,358,800,824]" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">type</typeStatus>
locality is at approximately 
<quantity box="[675,735,800,824]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="3" pageNumber="375" unit="m" value="40.0">40 m</quantity>
). No plant associations are available for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Caldwell" authorityYear="1951" box="[1185,1307,799,824]" class="Insecta" family="Delphacidae" genus="Abbrosoga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="375" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1185,1307,799,824]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">Abbrosoga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. At present the genus is only known from 
<collectingCountry box="[499,636,836,861]" name="Puerto Rico" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">Puerto Rico</collectingCountry>
; however, we have examined a single male specimen from 
<collectingCountry box="[1313,1436,836,861]" name="Costa Rica" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">Costa Rica</collectingCountry>
(La Selva Biological Station, UDCC) that is substantially similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Caldwell" authorityYear="1951" box="[938,1060,871,896]" class="Insecta" family="Delphacidae" genus="Abbrosoga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="375" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[938,1060,871,896]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">Abbrosoga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and may be placed in the genus once more material becomes available. We have also examined a specimen from 
<collectingCountry box="[1081,1149,908,933]" name="Brazil" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion box="[1166,1336,908,933]" country="Brazil" name="Santa Catarina" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">Santa Catarina</collectingRegion>
, UDCC) that has substantially similar male terminalia, but is much larger and darkly patterned and may be an allied undescribed genus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="375" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,1221]" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1015,1040]" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">Etymology.</emphasis>
The etymology of “ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Caldwell" authorityYear="1951" box="[584,706,1015,1040]" class="Insecta" family="Delphacidae" genus="Abbrosoga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="375" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[584,706,1015,1040]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">Abbrosoga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
” was not specified in 
<bibRefCitation author="Caldwell, J. S. &amp; Martorell, L. F." box="[986,1331,1015,1040]" pageId="3" pageNumber="375" pagination="133 - 269" refId="ref6483" refString="Caldwell, J. S. &amp; Martorell, L. F. (1951 dated 1950) Review of the Auchenorynchous Homoptera of Puerto Rico. Part II. The Fulgoroidea except Kinnaridae. Journal of Agriculture of the University of Puerto Rico, 34 (2), 133 - 269." type="journal article" year="1951">Caldwell &amp; Martorell (1951)</bibRefCitation>
, and the underlying meaning is not obvious to us. We speculate that the name is a truncation of the Latin word “ 
<emphasis box="[163,294,1087,1112]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">abbreviatus</emphasis>
” plus the Spanish word “ 
<emphasis box="[580,633,1089,1112]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">soga</emphasis>
” (rope), meaning ‘short rope’ a possible reference to the suspensorium. Also, plausibly the name may be comprised of the prefix “ 
<emphasis box="[814,842,1124,1149]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">ab</emphasis>
-̏ (away, from) plus a truncation of “ 
<emphasis box="[1263,1330,1124,1149]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">brosis</emphasis>
” (Greek, food), plus “- 
<emphasis box="[300,342,1161,1184]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="375">oga</emphasis>
” for euphony; or alternatively an arbitrary combination of letters. The name is treated as feminine in gender.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
